'''David Wetherall''' (born [[14 March]] [[1971]] in [[Sheffield]]) is a former [[England|English]] [[defender (football)|central defender]] who finished his playing career with [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] at the end of the 2007&ndash;08 season. He also served as the club's caretaker manager for three months in 2007. He supported [[Leeds United A.F.C.|Leeds United]] and started his playing career there, playing more than 200 games before he moved to Bradford City. He is now part of the club's coaching setup.

==Playing career==
===Trainee===
Wetherall began his career in 1989 with [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]]. He was studying for a [[Chemistry]] degree at the city's [[University of Sheffield|university]] and he represented Great Britain in the [[1991 Summer Universiade|1991 World Student Games]]&mdash;the football section was staged at venues around the region, including [[Valley Parade]]. He gained a first class honours degree in chemistry in 1992.<ref>[http://www.shef.ac.uk/alumni/known.html Well-known Sheffield Alumni]</ref>

===Leeds United===
He moved to [[Leeds United A.F.C.|Leeds United]] on [[15 July]] [[1991]] for <U+00A3>125,000. He made his debut against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] on [[24 February]] [[1993]] but it was not until the [[1994-95 in English football|1994&ndash;95]] that he became a regular in the Leeds team.

Wetherall played in the game when against arch-rivals [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] in 1997 when [[Roy Keane]] badly injured his knee. Keane later took revenge on [[Alf Inge Haaland]] during a Manchester derby and said to him as he lay on the ground: "And don't ever stand over me again sneering about fake injuries, and tell your pal (David) Wetherall there's some for him as well."<ref>{{cite news
|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/m/man_utd/2189742.stm
|title=Keane could face FA rap
|accessdate=2007-12-15
|date=[[13 August]] [[2002]]
|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>

David Wetherall will always be remembered fondly by Leeds fans in particular because he twiced scored against Manchester United, first in 1994 in a 2&ndash;1 win, and then the only goal in 1&ndash;0 in 1997.

He played more than 200 league games for Leeds scoring 12 goals. In total he appeared in 250 games.

===Bradford City===
After more than 200 league games in eight seasons at Leeds United, Wetherall left on [[30 June]] [[1999]] to join West Yorkshire rivals [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]], who paid a club record [[pound sterling|<U+00A3>]]1.4 million. Aged 28, he was signed to give experience to a Bradford side who had just been promoted to the [[Premier League|Premiership]]. Manager [[Paul Jewell]] had made a number of signings aged over 30, prompting journalists to call his team "Dad's Army".<ref>{{cite news
|url=http://archive.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/2000/2/17/156511.html
|title=Don't panic!
|date=[[17 February]] [[2000]]
|accessdate=2008-02-07
|publisher=Telegraph & Argus}}</ref> Bradford won their first game 1&ndash;0 with a last minute goal at [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] scored by [[Dean Saunders]] who started a celebration pouring scorn at the club's cynics. Wetherall's first goal for Bradford was in a [[Football League Cup|League Cup]] game at [[Reading F.C.|Reading]] before he scored again in the following round as City were knocked out by [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]].<ref>{{cite news
|url=http://archive.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/1999/10/13/160804.html
|title=City shot out of Worthington Cup
|date=[[13 October]] [[1999]]
|accessdate=2008-02-07
|publisher=Telegraph & Argus}}</ref> His first league goal came in a 2&ndash;0 win against [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] on [[18 December]] [[1999]].<ref>{{cite news
|url=http://archive.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/1999/12/20/158431.html
|title=City call the Toon!
|date=[[20 December]] [[2000]]
|accessdate=2008-02-07
|publisher=Telegraph & Argus}}</ref> Wetherall missed only two cups game for City during his first season,<ref>{{cite news
|url=http://archive.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/1999/9/15/161628.html
|title=Big let-down for City!
|date=[[15 September]] [[1999]]
|accessdate=2008-02-07
|publisher=Telegraph & Argus}}</ref><ref>{{cite news
|url=http://archive.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/1999/12/30/158168.html
|title=Wethers misses cup tie
|date=[[30 December]] [[1999]]
|accessdate=2008-02-07
|publisher=Telegraph & Argus}}</ref> and was the only player in the Premiership to have played every minute of the league season.<ref name="intertoto"/> His partnership with the emerging [[Andy O'Brien (footballer)|Andy O'Brien]] in central defence was the front line in City's survival attempt. But City went into the final game of the season facing possible [[promotion and relegation|relegation]].<ref>{{cite news
|url=http://archive.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/2000/5/13/153532.html
